land":"Brympton, Somerset, England","Brympton, Somerset, England":"Brympton, Somerset, England"},"en":{"1396–21 March 1420":"1396–21 March 1420","1396–1420":"1396–1420","1401–Male":"1401–Deceased","1420–1468":"1420–1468","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1468":"1468","1401":"1401","1411":"1411","1420":"1420","1396":"1396","1363":"1363","1350":"1350","21 March 1420":"21 March 1420","1360":"1360","Brimpton, Somerset, England":"Brympton, Somerset, England","Brympton, Somerset, England":"Brympton, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Whyton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Wyton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wyton","meanings":["English:  see  Whitton   (2)."]},{"name":"Whitton","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Whitton in Morebattle (Roxburghshire). The placename is from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farm, village’, as with many of the places in 2 below.","English: habitational name from any of the places called Whitton (Durham, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Northumberland, Shropshire, Suffolk) or Witton (Cheshire, Durham, Lancashire, Herefordshire, Norfolk, Northumberland, Warwickshire, Worcestershire, North Yorkshire); or possibly from Wyton (Huntingdonshire, East Yorkshire); or possibly from Weeton, Market Weighton, or Little Weighton (East Yorkshire). The placenames do not all share the same etymology but most of their post-medieval spellings are interchangeable. Most of the placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> or Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some, for example Witton in Warwickshire, derive from Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farmstead’ + <i>tūn</i>, and some others, for example Witton in Norfolk, derive from Old English <i>widu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>tūn</i>. Whitton in Lincolnshire derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> (genitive <i>Hwītan</i>) or Old English <i>hwīt</i> (dative <i>hwītan</i>) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. Witton in Lancashire derives from the Old English personal <i>Witta</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","English: in Devon, this surname is a variant of   Whiddon  ."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margery Whyton was born in 1396, in Brympton, Somerset, England, her father, John Whyton, was 46 and her mother, Joan Hussey, was 37. She had at least 1 son with Walter Sydenham. She died on 21 March 1420, at the age of 24."},"et":{"1396–21 March 1420":"1396–21. märts 1420","1396–1420":"1396–1420","1401–Male":"1401–Surnud","1420–1468":"1420–1468","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1468":"1468","1401":"1401","1411":"1411","1420":"1420","1396":"1396","1363":"1363","1350":"1350","21 March 1420":"21. märts 1420","1360":"1360","Brimpton, Somerset, England":"Brympton, Somerset, England","Brympton, Somerset, England":"Brympton, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"1396–21 March 1420":"1396–21. maaliskuuta 1420","1396–1420":"1396–1420","1401–Male":"1401–Kuollut","1420–1468":"1420–1468","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1468":"1468","1401":"1401","1411":"1411","1420":"1420","1396":"1396","1363":"1363","1350":"1350","21 March 1420":"21. maaliskuuta 1420","1360":"1360","Brimpton, Somerset, England":"Brympton, Somerset, England","Brympton, Somerset, England":"Brympton, Somerset, England"},"fr":{"1396–21 March 1420":"1396–21 mars 1420","1396–1420":"1396–1420","1401–Male":"1401–Décédé","1420–1468":"1420–1468","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1360–Female":"1360–Décédée","1468":"1468","1401":"1401","1411":"1411","1420":"1420","1396":"1396","1363"